title: Delta_Connection_Flight_4819
summary: This article describes a Delta Connection Flight 4819 accident that occurred on February 17, 2025, when a Bombardier CRJ900 regional jet crashed and overturned while landing at Toronto Pearson International Airport. While all 80 occupants survived the incident, 21 people were injured, and the accident is currently under investigation.
extract: Delta Connection Flight 4819 was a scheduled international passenger flight from Minneapolis–Saint Paul International Airport, United States, that crashed and overturned on the runway whe landing at Toronto Pearson International Airport, Canada, on a routine flight on February 17, 2025. The flight was operated by a Bombardier CRJ900 regional jet aircraft by Endeavor Air, a wholly owned subsidiary of Delta Air Lines.

'''Delta Connection Flight 4819''' was a scheduled international passenger flight from [[Minneapolis–Saint Paul International Airport]], United States, that crashed and overturned on the runway whe  landing at [[Toronto Pearson International Airport]], Canada, on a routine flight on February 17, 2025. The flight was operated by a [[Bombardier CRJ700 series|Bombardier CRJ900]] regional jet aircraft by [[Endeavor Air]], a wholly owned subsidiary of [[Delta Air Lines]].{{efn|name=Delta Connection}}

The flight had 80 people on board, consisting of 76 passengers and 4 crew members. All passengers and crew survived, but 21 injuries were reported.

== Background ==
=== Aircraft ===
The aircraft involved was a 16-year-old [[Bombardier CRJ700 series#CRJ900LR|Bombardier CRJ900LR]] with the tail number {{Airreg|N|932XJ|.}}<ref name="Hradecky 2025">{{Cite news |last=Hradecky |first=Simon |date=February 18, 2025 |title=Accident: Endeavor CRJ9 at Toronto on Feb 17th 2025, flipped over on landing |url=https://avherald.com/h?article=52439b47 |access-date=February 19, 2025 |work=[[The Aviation Herald]]}}</ref>

The CRJ900LR is a modified sub-variant of the CRJ900 series of regional jets produced by [[Bombardier Aviation|Bombardier]], designed for longer-range flights due to its higher [[maximum takeoff weight]] (MTOW) as compared to the base variant of the CRJ900, a jet commonly used to operate short- to medium-haul regional flights. This jet had been configured with a seating capacity for up to 76 passengers.<ref name=":0" /> The variant has a maximum range of {{convert|1828|nmi}},<ref name="Aircraft Commerce 2009">{{Cite news |date=October 2009 |title=Owner's & Operator's Guide: CRJ Family |url=https://www.aircraft-commerce.com/wp-content/uploads/aircraft-commerce-docs/Aircraft%20guides/CRJ%20FAMILY%20CF34%20FAMILY/ISSUE66_CRJGUIDE.pdf |access-date=19 February 2025 |work=Aircraft Commerce |issue=66}}</ref> a wingspan of 81 feet, 7 inches (24.9 m) and a length of 118 feet 11 inches (36 m) with a cabin cross-section length of 84 inches (2.13 m).<ref>{{Cite web |title=Airport Planning Manual |url=https://customer.aero.bombardier.com/webd/BAG/CustSite/BRAD/RACSDocument.nsf/51aae8b2b3bfdf6685256c300045ff31/ec63f8639ff3ab9d85257c1500635bd8/$FILE/ATTQF1EY.pdf/CRJ900APMR11.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20220506090933/https://customer.aero.bombardier.com/webd/BAG/CustSite/BRAD/RACSDocument.nsf/51aae8b2b3bfdf6685256c300045ff31/ec63f8639ff3ab9d85257c1500635bd8/$FILE/ATTQF1EY.pdf/CRJ900APMR11.pdf |archive-date=May 6, 2022 |access-date=February 17, 2025 |website=Bombardier}}</ref> The aircraft was fitted with two [[General Electric CF34|General Electric CF34-8C5]] turbofan engines.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |title=Bombardier CRJ-900 |url=https://www.delta.com/us/en/aircraft/bombardier/crj-900 |access-date=February 17, 2025 |website=Delta}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=CRJ900 Canadian Regional Jet |url=https://odin.tradoc.army.mil/WEG/Asset/20148e6a0b7b8c07b746a4f9c9869cab |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20250218075253/https://odin.tradoc.army.mil/WEG/Asset/20148e6a0b7b8c07b746a4f9c9869cab |archive-date=February 18, 2025 |access-date=February 17, 2025 |website=Oper

title: Elimination_Chamber:_Toronto
summary: The article discusses WWE's upcoming Elimination Chamber: Toronto event, scheduled for March 1, 2025, at Rogers Centre in Toronto, Canada. This will be WWE's first event at Rogers Centre since WrestleMania X8 in 2002, marking the fourth consecutive Elimination Chamber event outside the United States and notably will feature John Cena's final Elimination Chamber appearance before his retirement.
extract: Elimination Chamber: Toronto is an upcoming 2025 professional wrestling event produced by the American company WWE. It will be the 15th Elimination Chamber event and will take place on Saturday, March 1, 2025, at Rogers Centre in Toronto, Ontario, Canada. The event will air via pay-per-view (PPV) and livestreaming and will be held from all three of WWE's brand divisions. The event is based around the Elimination Chamber match, a type of multi-person elimination-based Steel Cage match in which championships or future opportunities at championships are at stake.

{{short description|2025 WWE pay-per-view and livestreaming event}} {{use mdy dates|date=November 2024}} {{Infobox wrestling event |name = Elimination Chamber: Toronto |image = Elimination Chamber - Toronto poster.jpg |caption = Promotional poster featuring [[John Cena]] |tagline = |promotion = [[WWE]] |brand = [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]]
[[SmackDown (WWE brand)|SmackDown]]
[[NXT (WWE brand)|NXT]] |date = March 1, 2025 |attendance = |venue = [[Rogers Centre]] |city = [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]] |wwenlast = [[NXT Vengeance Day (2025)|Vengeance Day]] |wwennext = [[NXT Stand & Deliver (2025)|Stand & Deliver]] |event = [[WWE Elimination Chamber|Elimination Chamber]] |lastevent2 = [[Elimination Chamber: Perth|Perth]] |nextevent2 = }} '''Elimination Chamber: Toronto''' (known as '''No Escape: Toronto''' in Germany) is an upcoming 2025 [[professional wrestling]] [[List of WWE pay-per-view and livestreaming supercards|event]] produced by the American company [[WWE]]. It will be the 15th [[WWE Elimination Chamber|Elimination Chamber]] event and will take place on Saturday, March 1, 2025, at [[Rogers Centre]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]]. The event will air via [[pay-per-view]] (PPV) and [[livestreaming]] and will be held from all three of WWE's [[WWE brand extension|brand divisions]]. The event is based around the [[Elimination Chamber]] match, a type of multi-person elimination-based [[Steel Cage match]] in which championships or future opportunities at championships are at stake. This will be the first Elimination Chamber event in Toronto and the first WWE event to be held at Rogers Centre since [[WrestleMania X8]] in 2002 when it was still known as the SkyDome. It will also be the second Elimination Chamber event in Canada after the [[Elimination Chamber (2023)|2023 edition]] and the fourth consecutive Elimination Chamber to be held outside of the United States. This will also be the final Elimination Chamber appearance of [[John Cena]] due to his retirement from professional wrestling at the end of 2025. ==Production== [[File:Toronto - ON - Rogers Centre2.jpg|thumb|upright|250px|The 2025 [[WWE Elimination Chamber|Elimination Chamber]] will be held at [[Rogers Centre]] in [[Toronto, Ontario, Canada]], which will be [[WWE]]'s first event in the stadium since [[WrestleMania X8]] in 2002.]] ===Background=== [[WWE Elimination Chamber|Elimination Chamber]] is a [[professional wrestling]] [[List of WWE pay-per-view and livestreaming supercards|event]] first produced by the American promotion [[WWE]] in 2010. It has been held every year since, except in 2016, generally in February. The [[Gimmick (professional wrestling)|concept]] of the event is that one or two [[Card (sports)#Main event|main event matches]] are contested inside the [[Elimination Chamber]], which is a type of multi-person elimination-based [[Steel Cage match]] in which championships or future opportunities at championships are at stake.{{cite web|url=https://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/2010/exclusives/chamberrules|title=Elimination Chamber Match rules|access-date=February 2, 2010|work=[[World Wrestling Entertainment]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110208084141/https://www.wwe.com/shows/eliminationchamber/history/2010/exclusives/chamberrules|archive-date=February 8, 2011}} Announced on November 8, 2024, the 15th Elimination Chamber event, titled as Elimination Chamber: Toronto, is scheduled to take place on Saturday, March 1, 2025, at [[Rogers Centre]] in [[Toronto]], [[Ontario]], [[Canada]], and will feature wrestlers from the [[Raw (WWE brand)|Raw]] and [[SmackDown]] [[WWE brand extension|brand divisions]].{{cite web |title=WWE Elimination Chamber 2025 Announced For Toronto |url=https://411mania.com/wrestling/wwe-elimination-chamber-2025-toronto/ |date=November 8, 2024 |last=Thomas |first=Jeremy |work=411Mania |access-date=November 8, 2024}} This will mark the second Elimination Chamber event to be held in Canada, after [[Elimination Chamber (2023)|2023]], and the fourth consecutive to be held outside of the United States, after the [[Elimination Chamber (2022)|2022]], 2023, and [[Elimination Chamber: Perth|2024]] events, which were held in [[Saudi Arabia]], Canada ([[Montreal]]), and [[Australia]], respectively. This will also mark WWE's first event to be held at the Rogers Centre since [[WrestleMania X8]] in 2002 when the stadium was still known as the SkyDome. This will also be the second Elimination Chamber event to have a subtitle named after its host city and to take place in an outdoor venue, both after 2024.{{cite news|last=Lambert|first=Jeremy|title=WWE Elimination Chamber 2024 To Take Place At Opt

title: Rick_Buckler
summary: This article is about Rick Buckler (1955-2025), who was the drummer of the influential British rock band The Jam. After his time with The Jam, Buckler worked with various other bands and briefly left music to work as a carpenter, before returning to perform Jam material with the band From the Jam until 2009.
